<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is a prime number?", answer: "A prime number is a natural number greater than 1 that has no positive divisors other than 1 and itself. In other words, a prime number can only be divided evenly by 1 and the number itself. The first few prime numbers are 2, 3, 5, 7, 11, 13, 17, 19, 23, and 29. The number 2 is the only even prime number; all other even numbers are divisible by 2 and therefore not prime. Prime numbers are fundamental building blocks in mathematics because every positive integer greater than 1 can be uniquely represented as a product of prime numbers (the fundamental theorem of arithmetic)." },
  { question: "What is prime factorization?", answer: "Prime factorization is the process of expressing a composite number as a product of its prime factors. For example, 60 = 2 x 2 x 3 x 5. Every composite number has a unique prime factorization (up to the order of the factors), which is guaranteed by the fundamental theorem of arithmetic. Prime factorization is used in cryptography, particularly in RSA encryption, where the security relies on the difficulty of factoring very large numbers into their prime components. It is also used in simplifying fractions, finding GCD and LCM, and solving various number theory problems." },
  { question: "How do you check if a number is prime?", answer: "The most basic method is trial division: divide the number by all integers from 2 up to the square root of the number. If none divide evenly, the number is prime. You can optimize by checking only odd numbers after checking for divisibility by 2. More advanced algorithms include the Miller-Rabin primality test (probabilistic) and the AKS primality test (deterministic polynomial time). For numbers up to about 10 billion, trial division with square root optimization is efficient enough for instant results." },
  { question: "Why are prime numbers important?", answer: "Prime numbers are the building blocks of all integers and are fundamental to number theory. In practical applications, they are essential for modern cryptography (RSA, Diffie-Hellman key exchange), hash functions, random number generation, and error-correcting codes. The security of internet banking, e-commerce, and encrypted communications all depend on properties of prime numbers, specifically the computational difficulty of factoring large numbers into their prime components." },
  { question: "Is 1 a prime number?", answer: "No, 1 is not a prime number. By definition, a prime number must be greater than 1 and have exactly two distinct positive divisors: 1 and itself. The number 1 has only one divisor (itself), so it does not meet the definition. This convention was established in the early 20th century to preserve the uniqueness of prime factorization guaranteed by the fundamental theorem of arithmetic. If 1 were considered prime, the factorization of any number would not be unique because you could include any number of 1s as factors." }
]) %>

